<br>  Hello Bhaskar Chowdhury,<br>

If you have more than one split in Vim, and you want to scroll
them together (for example two vertical splits), here's what you
need to do:

- In each window that should scroll simultaneously, enter the
command: :set scrollbind

You can enter scb as an abbreviation for scrollbind.

You might now that ! flag causes :set to toggle a boolean
configuration option.
Therefore, you can easily toggle scrollbind on or off by running:

:set scb!

That's all for today. You won't be using this tip very often, but
it's good to know it's possible.

Cheers,
Jovica

P.S.

Here's what J. Castelain had to say about Mastering Vim Quickly (
https://el2.convertkit-mail.com/c/e5u8emrgona0uw8mkzi8/reh8hohe0kq9w/aHR0cD=
ovL2pvdmljYWlsaWMub3JnL21hc3RlcmluZy12aW0tcXVpY2tseS8=3D ):

>The specific features you liked most about "Mastering Vim
Quickly"?

"I think this book is different in the sense that it is more
"efficient" than other books when it comes to teaching stuff. I
usually read a chapter during my commute and use what I read in
my daily work flow, this has been very effective for me, and I
think the author really knows what he's talking about. It's like
if I was sitting next to a vim master."

>Would you recommend this book and why?

"Yes I would.
I've read several books on vim and for me this is the best one.
It covers essential topics that will get beginners started and
comfortable with vim and also teaches more advanced tips for
experienced "vimmers"."

